

UI System Testing

Definition

UI System Testing validates the complete user interface of the application in an integrated environment to ensure it behaves correctly from an end-user perspective. It confirms that UI components function cohesively with backend services, business logic, and data layers.

This testing is performed after integration and focuses on validating the system as a whole through the user interface.

⸻

Objectives
	•	Validate end-to-end user workflows through the UI
	•	Ensure UI components correctly interact with backend services
	•	Verify navigation, page transitions, and user journeys
	•	Confirm data consistency between UI and underlying systems
	•	Validate cross-browser and responsive behavior (if in scope)

⸻

Identification Criteria

A scenario falls under UI System Testing when:
	•	The test validates complete workflows across multiple screens
	•	Backend integration is indirectly validated through UI behavior
	•	User role-based access or permissions are verified through UI
	•	System behavior is validated in a production-like environment

⸻

Scope Coverage

UI System Testing typically includes:
	•	End-to-end business flows
	•	Navigation validation
	•	Role-based access validation
	•	UI interaction with APIs and database
	•	Error handling at system level
	•	Browser compatibility (if applicable)
	•	Basic usability and rendering consistency

⸻

Example Scenarios

Example 1 – User Registration Flow
	•	User fills registration form
	•	System validates input
	•	Account is created in database
	•	Confirmation email is triggered
	•	User is redirected to login page

This validates UI behavior along with backend integration.

⸻

Example 2 – Booking Flow
	•	User selects available slot
	•	Slot availability updates dynamically
	•	Payment is processed
	•	Booking confirmation displayed
	•	Booking record stored and retrievable

This scenario validates full system behavior through UI.

⸻

Entry Criteria
	•	Build deployed in integrated environment
	•	Core modules integrated
	•	APIs available and stable

⸻

Exit Criteria
	•	Critical and major UI workflow defects resolved
	•	Core business journeys validated successfully

⸻

UI Form Validation Testing

Definition

UI Form Validation Testing focuses specifically on validating input controls, field-level validations, and user feedback mechanisms within forms.

This testing ensures that data entered by users adheres to defined validation rules before submission.

⸻

Objectives
	•	Verify mandatory field validations
	•	Validate format and data type restrictions
	•	Confirm boundary and length constraints
	•	Ensure proper error messaging
	•	Prevent invalid data submission

⸻

Identification Criteria

A scenario falls under UI Form Validation Testing when:
	•	It validates field-level rules
	•	It tests invalid or malformed inputs
	•	It verifies inline validation messages
	•	It ensures client-side and/or server-side validation enforcement

⸻

Types of Validations Covered

1. Mandatory Field Validation
	•	Required fields cannot be left empty

2. Format Validation
	•	Email format
	•	Phone number format
	•	Date format

3. Length Validation
	•	Minimum and maximum character limits

4. Data Type Validation
	•	Numeric-only fields
	•	Alphabet-only fields

5. Boundary Validation
	•	Minimum and maximum value limits

⸻

Example Scenarios

Example 1 – Email Field Validation
	•	Enter invalid email format → Error displayed
	•	Enter valid email format → Accepted
	•	Leave email empty → Mandatory field error

⸻

Example 2 – Password Field Validation

Password rules: 8–20 characters, at least one special character
	•	7 characters → Rejected
	•	8 characters without special character → Rejected
	•	8 characters with special character → Accepted
	•	21 characters → Rejected

⸻

Example 3 – Numeric Input Field
	•	Enter alphabets in numeric field → Rejected
	•	Enter special characters → Rejected
	•	Enter valid numeric value within limit → Accepted

⸻

Validation Layers

UI Form Validation Testing may include:
	•	Client-side validation (immediate feedback)
	•	Server-side validation (upon submission)
	•	Error message consistency and clarity
	•	Prevention of bypass through direct API calls (if in scope)

⸻

Key Distinction

UI System Testing validates complete user journeys and system behavior through the interface.

UI Form Validation Testing focuses specifically on field-level input validation within forms.

Form validation is a subset of UI testing but may be executed independently during development or feature-level validation.

